🚀 1. CLH Queue (Used by AQS)
🧠 Idea
👉 AQS uses a variant of CLH (Craig–Landin–Hagersten) queue
Thread waits on predecessor’s state

🔹 Structure
HEAD ← T1 ← T2 ← T3 ← T4
Each thread:


Knows its previous node


Spins or parks based on it



🔥 Key Concept
👉 Thread doesn’t spin on global lock
👉 It watches its predecessor

💻 Simplified Model
while (pred.isLocked()) {    // wait}

✅ Advantages


Less contention


Scalable


Used in AQS



⚠️ Limitation


Needs implicit linking (prev pointer)



⚔️ 2. MCS Queue (Alternative Design)
🧠 Idea
👉 Each thread has its own node
Each thread spins on its own state

🔹 Structure
T1 → T2 → T3 → T4
Each node has:


locked flag


next pointer



💻 Simplified Code
class Node {    volatile boolean locked = true;    Node next;}

🔁 Flow
Thread joins queue → spins on its own flag → predecessor unlocks it

✅ Advantages


No global contention


Better NUMA performance



⚠️ Compared to CLH
FeatureCLHMCSSpin onpredecessorselfMemoryimplicitexplicitUsed in Java✅❌

🔥 3. CAS (Compare-And-Swap)
🧠 Core Operation
if (current == expected) → updateelse → fail

💻 Example
import java.util.concurrent.atomic.AtomicInteger;public class CASExample {    static AtomicInteger counter = new AtomicInteger(0);    public static void main(String[] args) {        counter.compareAndSet(0, 1);        System.out.println(counter.get());    }}

🔁 CAS Loop (Important)
while (true) {    int old = counter.get();    int newVal = old + 1;    if (counter.compareAndSet(old, newVal)) {        break;    }}

⚠️ Problems
❗ ABA Problem
A → B → A (CAS thinks nothing changed ❌)

✅ Fix
Use:
AtomicStampedReference

⚡ 4. VarHandle (Modern Low-Level API)
👉 Replacement for Unsafe

💻 Example
import java.lang.invoke.MethodHandles;import java.lang.invoke.VarHandle;public class VarHandleExample {    static class Counter {        int value;    }    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {        VarHandle HANDLE = MethodHandles.lookup()                .findVarHandle(Counter.class, "value", int.class);        Counter c = new Counter();        HANDLE.compareAndSet(c, 0, 10);        System.out.println(c.value);    }}

🧠 Why important?


Fine-grained control


Used in JDK internals


High performance



🚀 5. Lock-Free Programming
🧠 Definition
👉 No locks
👉 Only CAS + atomic ops

💻 Example (Lock-Free Counter)
import java.util.concurrent.atomic.AtomicInteger;public class LockFreeCounter {    AtomicInteger counter = new AtomicInteger();    public void increment() {        counter.incrementAndGet();    }}

✅ Benefits


No blocking


No deadlocks


High throughput



⚠️ Drawbacks


Complex


Hard to debug


Starvation possible



🔥 6. Disruptor Pattern (VERY IMPORTANT)
👉 Used in:


Trading systems


High-speed messaging


Low latency pipelines



🧠 Idea
Ring buffer instead of queue

🔹 Structure
[Slot0][Slot1][Slot2][Slot3]...(circular)

🔥 Why fast?


No locks


No GC pressure


Cache-friendly



💻 Simplified Example
class RingBuffer {    private final int[] buffer = new int[4];    private int writeIndex = 0;    public void publish(int value) {        buffer[writeIndex % buffer.length] = value;        writeIndex++;    }    public int get(int index) {        return buffer[index % buffer.length];    }}

🧠 Key Concepts


Sequence numbers


Memory barriers


False sharing avoidance



⚠️ 7. Real Production Issues

❌ False Sharing
Two threads modifying nearby variables → cache contention

✅ Fix
Padding / @Contended

❌ CAS Spin High CPU
Too many retries → CPU spike

❌ Lock-free ≠ bug-free
Still can have:


race conditions


livelocks



